message.content: A merism is a type of word problem in logic and mathematics where two expressions are compared on equal terms but differ in their structure or form. This concept is often used to clarify concepts in set theory, combinatorics, algebra and other branches of mathematics. For example, the expression (a+b) - (c + d) = (ac - bd) which diffends from the equation (a+b)-(c+d)=ad-bc. Here a,b,c,d are any real numbers.
